Face2Age

Predicting a person's age (work-in-progress)

Nov 15, 2020 • Jesse van Elteren • 4 min read

Deep learning has seen incredible results the last couple of year. As long as you have a large enough dataset, you can transform any input to an arbitrary output. Two examples:

  • Image classification where you map an image to a label (image of a frog à computer outputs ‘frog’)
  • Sentence generation (if I start a sentence with ‘The sun is’, computer outputs ‘a huge bowl of molten lava’.
  • Recommender system (which is the next video that will keep you watching as much as possible) As an aside, I’ve added the last one, since systems used on social media are executing their task so well, but a by effect is it radicalizes people. So deep learning is not without it’s ethical problems!

In this project, I’ve taken on a image regression problem. Given an image of someone’s face, how well can we predict the age of that person? It’s a nice problem, because the answer is not always obvious: some people look older or younger than they really are. Initially the model gives more or less random predictions, but with showing it more examples and giving feedback how wrong it was, it improves itself. We don’t have to explain anything about how an old or young person looks like. Can you imagine the nightmare of trying to code how to recognize wrinkles? This is essentially the wonder of neural networks.

When training a model, an important part of its performance is the metric you choose. For this task of guessing someone’s age, I’ve chosen Mean Absolute Error, basically how many years you’ve guessed wrong. A prediction of 12 on a real age of 10 means the MAE is 2, just as a prediction of 8 would have.

The dataset contains about 10.000 images, I’ve trained the model on 70% of the dataset. That leaves about 3k images which the model has not seen yet and we can test it’s performance. In theory, this performance would also apply to other unseen images. In practice that remains to be seen, since the images can differ in quality, zoom in level on the face and background.

We show this training dataset 30 times (epochs) to the model, and below you can see it getting better over time. The left graph shows performance on the training set, the right graph on the test set. Initially, it’s off by about 11 years, and slowly converging to a MAE of 2 years. But that is the performance in the training set, and we are interested in it’s performance on unseen images! The performance there converges to around 4.4.

The MAE of the model on the validation dataset is 4.4. Let's check out some predictions.

Looks pretty good! To ensure let's plot the predictions and actuals in a graph.

<!DOCTYPE svg PUBLIC "-//W3C//DTD SVG 1.1//EN" "http://www.w3.org/Graphics/SVG/1.1/DTD/svg11.dtd">

Still nice. It's also interesting to understand for which faces the error was largest. As you can see below, in most of the cases the model was simply off, but there are also faces which look much older or younger. Which highlights the importance of understanding the dataset and potentially cleaning it from outliers.

<!DOCTYPE svg PUBLIC "-//W3C//DTD SVG 1.1//EN" "http://www.w3.org/Graphics/SVG/1.1/DTD/svg11.dtd">

Also an interesting pattern is visible in the average error by age. The error gets larger as someone gets older, which makes perfect sense. If you see a baby you are not going to guess wrong by more then 5 years, but for someone age 50 that is way more difficult. Maybe there is also a slight trend of better predictions when people are > 70, but it could also be an anomaly. Also there are few really old faces in the dataset. Also there are many babies in the dataset!

<!DOCTYPE svg PUBLIC "-//W3C//DTD SVG 1.1//EN" "http://www.w3.org/Graphics/SVG/1.1/DTD/svg11.dtd">

I’ve also build a webpage where you can try out if you can beat the computer, or even upload a selfie to see the results. I’ve taken some selfies and the computer estimated me around 27 to 42, which is ballpark accurate. But an condolence card of my grandmother age 92 was classified as 62. She did look young, but 62 was a bit of an underestimation…

That’s it, I’ve had much fun with this project. I hope you’ve liked it as well and will try out the app. Click here to see if we collectively can outperform the computer.

Note: Technical details on how it was build: Pytorch, Pretrained resnet-18 model. Application runs on Google Cloud Platform, with a Nginx and Gunicorn running in Docker container. Python backend in Fastapi. Code available on Github, dataset on Kaggle
